  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (950d863 2023-10-25T11:49:15.075206396Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\n```solidity\r\nfunction test_minimal() public {\r\n    assertTrue(false);\r\n    vm.expectRevert();\r\n}\r\n\r\n// [FAIL. Reason: Call did not revert as expected]\r\n```\r\n\r\nGiven the toy example above, one may expect something like `Assertion failed` because of  `assertTrue(false);` but instead `Call did not revert as expected` emitted.\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\nfunction test_minimal() public {\r\n    vm.expectRevert();\r\n    _itReverts();\r\n    this._call();\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunction _itReverts() internal {\r\n    // Arithmetic over/underflow\r\n    type(uint256).max + 1;\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunction _call() external {\r\n    // nop\r\n}\r\n\r\n// [PASS] test_minimal() (gas: 3178)\r\n```\r\n\r\nGiven another example, one may expect something like `[FAIL. Reason: Arithmetic over/underflow]` but instead it looks like the `vm.expectRevert` inspects the test function call itself (just my guess) and silently passes the test. With no `this._call();` it works in the same way.",
